Friday September 13th 2013 2:11 pm -04:00,I was just explaining stacks today to some of my engineering students who code in assembler and could not be called experienced programmers by anybodys standards (they are a nice group and do try very hard though).in assembler you mostly have to move values about between registers.  Lets say you added two numbers and the answer is in the AH register.  You want to output the answer to the screen but the graphics card also uses the AH register.  If you try to output anything you will end up overwriting the answer.So you push the answer in AH onto the stack to keep it safe.  You then use the AH register to do the display bit.  Then you pop the stack to bring back the answer and carry on from where you left off.You can have many items in the stack but they always go on top of each other and are removed again in a LIFO (last in first out) order.  You cant change the order of things once they are on a stack.  If you try to remove an item from an already empty stack you get an underflow.  If you havent allowed enough room for your stack at the start it can overflow (everything just dumps and crashes and you usually get the Blue Screen Of Death).  And experienced programmers do quite often use tools like the visualiser to step through code but they are usually called debugging tools.  They are not always separate from the main development interface sometimes its just a step-through option but its the same sort of thing.  It enables you to run your code a line at a time so you can see exactly where it falls over., Resolved,1
